## Topic 4: Transformations on the Plane — Shifting, Scaling, Reflecting

### History and Meaning

A *transformation* is a rule that moves every point in the plane to a new location. The ancient Greeks studied reflections and rotations as symmetries. In the 19th century, Felix Klein proposed that geometry *is* the study of transformations — what properties stay the same when you move, flip, or stretch a shape? Transformations are the heartbeat of computer graphics: every time you drag a window, rotate a photo, or zoom in, you're applying a transformation to a grid of pixels.

**Uses in the world:** GPS coordinates are transformed between different map projections. 3D graphics engines transform objects from world space to camera space to screen space. Architects flip and rotate blueprints. MRI scans are built by transforming slices into a 3D volume.

**What we'll cover:** We'll shift a shape (translation), stretch it (scaling), flip it (reflection), and eventually rotate it. Each transformation is a function that takes a point *(x, y)* and gives you a new point *(x', y')*.

**In Motoi:** Transformations are how she *reuses* shapes. Draw a triangle once, then shift it, scale it, flip it, rotate it — infinite variations from one template.

---

### Example 34: Translate a point — shift right 3, up 2

<!-- BUILD: add (3, 2) to a point -->

```scheme
(define translate
  (lambda (pt dx dy)
    (geom/point (+ (geom/point-x pt) dx)
                (+ (geom/point-y pt) dy))))

(define original (geom/point 1 1))
(define shifted (translate original 3 2))

(display \"Original point: (1, 1)\")
(newline)
(display \"After shifting right 3, up 2: \")
(display shifted)
(newline)
```

[VISUAL: text output showing \"After shifting: (4, 3)\"]

---

### Example 35: Translate a list of points (a shape)

<!-- BUILD: map translation over a list of points -->

```scheme
(define translate-point
  (lambda (pt dx dy)
    (geom/point (+ (geom/point-x pt) dx)
                (+ (geom/point-y pt) dy))))

(define triangle
  (list (geom/point 0 0)
        (geom/point 2 0)
        (geom/point 1 2)))

(define shifted-triangle
  (map (lambda (pt) (translate-point pt 3 1)) triangle))

(display \"Original triangle vertices: \")
(display triangle)
(newline)
(display \"Shifted right 3, up 1: \")
(display shifted-triangle)
(newline)
```

[VISUAL: text output showing two lists of points]

---

### Example 36: Plot original and translated triangle

<!-- BUILD: plot two sets of points to show before and after -->

```scheme
(define tri-original
  (list (geom/point 0 0)
        (geom/point 2 0)
        (geom/point 1 2)))

(define tri-shifted
  (map (lambda (pt) (geom/point (+ (geom/point-x pt) 3)
                                 (+ (geom/point-y pt) 1)))
       tri-original))

(define orig-x (map geom/point-x tri-original))
(define orig-y (map geom/point-y tri-original))
(define shift-x (map geom/point-x tri-shifted))
(define shift-y (map geom/point-y tri-shifted))

(define translation-plot
  (plot/with
    (plot/scatter orig-x orig-y)
    (plot/scatter shift-x shift-y)))

(plot/render-svg translation-plot)
```

