## Topic 6: The Pythagorean Theorem — Right Triangles and Distance

### History and Meaning

The Pythagorean theorem — *a² + b² = c²* for the sides of a right triangle — is named after Pythagoras (c. 570–495 BCE), though the Babylonians knew it a thousand years earlier. It's one of the most famous equations in all of mathematics. It tells you that in any right triangle, the square of the hypotenuse (the side opposite the right angle) equals the sum of the squares of the other two sides. It's the *reason* the distance formula works, and the foundation of trigonometry.

**Uses in the world:** Carpenters use it to check if a corner is square (the \"3-4-5 rule\"). Surveyors use it to measure distances. GPS systems use a three-dimensional version to triangulate your position. Computer graphics use it millions of times per second to calculate distances between points.

**What we'll cover:** We'll verify Pythagorean triples (integer solutions like 3-4-5), use the theorem to find missing sides, and connect it to the distance formula on the coordinate plane.

**In Motoi:** The Pythagorean theorem is her tape measure. Any time she needs to know the straight-line distance between two points on the canvas, she's using this 2,500-year-old piece of mathematics.

---

### Example 56: Verify the 3-4-5 triple

<!-- BUILD: check that 3² + 4² = 5² -->

```scheme
(define a 3)
(define b 4)
(define c 5)

(define a-squared (* a a))
(define b-squared (* b b))
(define c-squared (* c c))

(display a)
(display \"² + \")
(display b)
(display \"² = \")
(display a-squared)
(display \" + \")
(display b-squared)
(display \" = \")
(display (+ a-squared b-squared))
(newline)
(display c)
(display \"² = \")
(display c-squared)
(newline)
(display \"Is it a Pythagorean triple? \")
(display (= (+ a-squared b-squared) c-squared))
(newline)
```

[VISUAL: text output showing \"9 + 16 = 25, 5² = 25, Is it a Pythagorean triple? #t\"]

---

### Example 57: Verify 5-12-13

<!-- BUILD: check another Pythagorean triple -->

```scheme
(define a 5)
(define b 12)
(define c 13)

(display a)
(display \"² + \")
(display b)
(display \"² = \")
(display (+ (* a a) (* b b)))
(newline)
(display c)
(display \"² = \")
(display (* c c))
(newline)
(display \"Triple? \")
(display (= (+ (* a a) (* b b)) (* c c)))
(newline)
```

[VISUAL: text output showing \"25 + 144 = 169, 13² = 169, Triple? #t\"]

